<p>Colonel Michael Randrianirina was sworn in as Madagascar’s president on Friday, days after the military seized power following weeks of youth-led demonstrations [dw.com#1][france24.com#1]. The shift came amid allegations of security force defections and after President Andry Rajoelina left the country during the upheaval [scmp.com#1]. The oath marked a swift transition at the height of the political turmoil, with the ceremony held in the capital’s judicial complex [firstpost.com#1].</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/nv7WX-csOxoRzDWydP3_FS8LJ2IeH7sF0M857tRgI-75WH-qnSHm5k4pwze468BNh1UgGimE7-zEoVJHRdAQDqmdaVqYuiBWb95NtPqXUnPPkR8LiitWzPEVzMVj2bjRIVWyggXqnqZBF07WNBwXUsPczlGv925os5TfRJAbqMI4146SBg1eiFHBTglxnOjLFiGo13Ichmmrmj9e7nUnQdgt1rprp62_wyeVXcbVSqb8xLe1xI0mV5F1yGYG1bt1m5SE3yKB2WwydupS6T8' alt='Colonel Michaël Randrianirina after his inauguration at the Constitutional Court in Antananarivo on October 17, 2025.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Ceremony details: Randrianirina took the oath in the main chamber of the High Constitutional Court, three days after the military seized power [firstpost.com#1][france24.com#1].</li><li>Protest drivers: The recent demonstrations were fueled by widespread power and water shortages in the country [aljazeera.com#2].</li><li>Elite background: Before taking power, Randrianirina served as commander of an elite army unit, identified by some outlets as CAPSAT [france24.com#1][dw.com#3].</li><li>Parliament move: Lawmakers impeached Andry Rajoelina during the crisis, according to local reporting cited by international media [scmp.com#1].</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Colonel Michael Randrianirina: Said he is open to talks with the African Union following the country’s suspension. (<a href='https://www.straitstimes.com/world/Army-colonel-plans-to-lead-Madagascar-after-coup-ousts-civilian-president'>The Straits Times</a>)</li><li>Andry Rajoelina: Condemned the takeover and has refused to step down while abroad. (<a href=